    #Remind me to look into tuples and how they work in Python, I have a basic understanding but I want to deepen my knowledge on them.

    #converting the color space from BGR to HSV wait why is it BGR and not RGB? I thought it was RGB? I guess OpenCV uses BGR by default for some reason
    hsvFrame = cv2.cvtColor(imageFrame, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV)
    #so thecvtColor is a function in the cv2 module or is it library? I think it is a function that is used to convert an image from one color space to another. In this case, we are converting the image from the BGR color space (which is the default color space used by OpenCV) to the HSV color space. 
    #The cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV is a constant that specifies the type of conversion we want to perform, which in this case is from BGR to HSV. By using this function, we can easily convert the image to the HSV color space, which can make it easier to detect specific colors based on their hue and saturation values.
    #the function takes how many arguments? I see it takes 2 arguments, the first one is the image we want to convert and the second one is the type of conversion we want to perform. So in this case, we are passing the imageFrame as the first argument and cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV as the second argument to specify that we want to convert from BGR to HSV color space.
    #what other type of conversions does the function support? I know it supports a variety of conversions, such as RGB to Grayscale, RGB to YUV, and many more. I will have to look into the documentation to see all the different types of conversions that are supported by the cvtColor function.

    #Defining the lower and upper bounds for the color detection that is I define the color ranges for the colors I want to detect. For example, if I want to detect red color, I can define the lower and upper bounds for the hue, saturation, and value (HSV) as follows:

    #setting range for red color
    red_lower = np.array([136, 87, 111], np.uint8)
    red_upper = np.array([180, 255, 255], np.uint8)
    #so the np.array is a function in the NumPy library that is used to create an array. In this case, we are creating two arrays, red_lower and red_upper, which define the lower and upper bounds for the hue, saturation, and value (HSV) for the red color. The values in the arrays represent the minimum and maximum values for each of the HSV components that we want to detect. By defining these bounds, we can create a mask that highlights the areas of the image that fall within this color range.
    #But who defines the values for the lower and upper bounds? I assume it is based on experimentation and observation. I can use a color picker tool to find the HSV values for the specific shade of red I want to detect, and then adjust the lower and upper bounds accordingly to ensure that I am capturing the desired range of colors.
    #Also I understand that the np.uint8 is a data type that specifies that the values in the array should be treated as unsigned 8-bit integers, which means they can range from 0 to 255. This is important because the HSV values for hue, saturation, and value are typically represented as integers in this range, so using np.uint8 ensures that the values are correctly interpreted when we create the mask for color detection.
    #Another Question I have is for red for example what is the difference between [136, 87, 111] and maybe others are these values universally fixed for red lower bound? I think they can vary depending on the specific shade of red you want to detect and the lighting conditions in the image. The values for the lower and upper bounds can be adjusted based on experimentation to ensure that you are capturing the desired range of colors. So while there may be some general guidelines for the HSV values for red, it is not necessarily fixed and can be fine-tuned based on your specific use case and the characteristics of the images you are working with.
    #But I thought we are using HSV because it is not affected by lighting conditions, so why would we need to adjust the values based on lighting? I guess while HSV can help mitigate some of the effects of lighting, it is not completely immune to it. Different lighting conditions can still affect the appearance of colors in an image, and as a result, you may need to adjust the lower and upper bounds for color detection to account for these variations. For example, under different lighting conditions, the same shade of red may appear slightly different in terms of its hue and saturation values, so you may need to fine-tune the bounds to ensure that you are accurately detecting the desired color range in various lighting scenarios.

    #defineing the mask for red color
    red_mask = cv2.inRange(hsvFrame, red_lower, red_upper)
    #the inRange function is a function in the OpenCV library that is used to create a binary mask based on the specified lower and upper bounds for color detection. In this case, we are using the inRange function to create a mask for the red color by passing the HSV image (hsvFrame) and the defined lower and upper bounds (red_lower and red_upper) as arguments. The function will return a binary mask where the pixels that fall within the specified color range will be set to 255 (white), and the pixels that do not fall within the range will be set to 0 (black). This mask can then be used to isolate and highlight the areas of the image that contain the red color we want to detect.
    #Having a hard time the concept of a mask and why it is called binary, I understand that it is a binary image because it only contains two values (0 and 255), but I am not sure why it is called a mask. I think it is called a mask because it acts as a filter that allows us to isolate specific parts of the image based on the color we want to detect. By applying the mask to the original image, we can effectively "mask out" the areas that do not contain the desired color, leaving us with only the regions of interest that we want to analyze further. So in this sense, the mask serves as a tool to focus our attention on specific colors in the image while ignoring the rest. Also is the mask based on thebounds we set for the color detection?
    # After looking it up, Yes, the mask is directly based on the lower and upper bounds we defined for the color detection. The inRange function uses these bounds to determine which pixels in the HSV image fall within the specified color range, and it creates the binary mask accordingly. So if we adjust the bounds, we will see a different mask that highlights different areas of the image based on the new color range we have defined.

    #green color
    green_lower = np.array([25, 52, 72], np.uint8)
    green_upper = np.array([102, 255, 255], np.uint8)
    green_mask = cv2.inRange(hsvFrame, green_lower, green_upper)

    #blue color
    blue_lower = np.array([94, 80, 2], np.uint8)
    blue_upper = np.array([120, 255, 255], np.uint8) #what would be different if I set Hue to 126 instead of the 120? I think it would allow us to detect a slightly wider range of blue colors, including some shades that may have a hue value around 126. By increasing the upper bound for the hue, we can capture a broader spectrum of blue colors in the image, which may be beneficial if we want to ensure that we are detecting all relevant shades of blue. However, it is important to be cautious when adjusting the bounds, as setting them too wide may result in false positives and include colors that are not actually blue. So it is a balance between capturing the desired range of colors and avoiding unwanted detections.
    blue_mask = cv2.inRange(hsvFrame, blue_lower, blue_upper)

    #combining the masks, what even is that and why do we need to combine them? I think combining the masks allows us to create a single mask that highlights all the colors we want to detect in the image. By using a bitwise OR operation (cv2.bitwise_or), we can combine the individual masks for red, green, and blue into one comprehensive mask that captures all the specified color ranges. This way, we can easily apply this combined mask to the original image to isolate and analyze all the relevant colors in one step, rather than having to apply each mask separately.
    #why not bitwise AND? I think using a bitwise AND operation would not be appropriate in this case because it would only highlight the pixels that are common to all the masks, which means we would only detect the colors that fall within the intersection of the defined color ranges. This would likely result in very few detections, as it is unlikely that many pixels will simultaneously meet the criteria for being red, green, and blue at the same time. On the other hand, using a bitwise OR operation allows us to capture any pixel that falls within any of the defined color ranges, giving us a more comprehensive detection of all the relevant colors in the image.
    #Let me start with bitwise and and see what happens, I want to see the difference between the two operations in terms of the resulting mask and the colors that are detected. This will help me understand the practical implications of using bitwise AND versus bitwise OR for combining the masks in color detection.

    #creating mask
    
    #to detect only that particular color
    kernel = np.ones((5, 5), "uint8") #what is a kernel and why do we need it? I think a kernel is a small matrix that is used in image processing to perform operations such as blurring, sharpening, and edge detection. In the context of color detection, we can use a kernel to apply morphological operations to the mask, such as dilation or erosion, which can help to improve the quality of the mask by filling in gaps or removing noise. By applying these operations with the kernel, we can enhance the detected regions of color and make them more distinct in the resulting image.

    #dilation is a morphological operation that can be applied to the mask to enhance the detected regions of color. It works by adding pixels to the boundaries of the detected regions, effectively expanding them. This can help to fill in small gaps or holes in the detected areas, making them more solid and easier to analyze. By applying dilation with a kernel, we can improve the visibility of the detected colors in the image and make it easier to identify and track them.
    red_mask = cv2.dilate(red_mask, kernel) #so dilate takes the mask and the kernel as arguments and applies the dilation operation to the mask using the specified kernel. The result is an enhanced version of the red_mask where the detected regions of red color are expanded, making them more prominent in the resulting image. This can help to improve the accuracy of color detection by ensuring that we capture all relevant areas of the image that contain the desired color.
    #So the kernel is an array? Yes, the kernel is a small matrix (in this case, a 5x5 array of ones) that is used to define the neighborhood for the dilation operation. The values in the kernel determine how the dilation is applied to the mask, with the ones indicating which pixels should be considered for expansion during the dilation process. By using this kernel, we can control the extent of dilation and how it affects the detected regions of color in the mask.
    #Trying to find oout what happens if I change the size of the kernel, for example to (3, 3) or (7, 7). I want to see how it affects the dilation process and the resulting mask. A smaller kernel may result in less expansion of the detected regions, while a larger kernel may lead to more significant dilation, potentially filling in larger gaps but also increasing the risk of merging nearby regions together. By experimenting with different kernel sizes, I can find the optimal balance for enhancing the detected colors without losing important details or creating unwanted connections between separate regions.
    res_red = cv2.bitwise_and(imageFrame, imageFrame, mask = red_mask) #what does the bitwise_and function do in this context? I think the bitwise_and function is used to apply the red_mask to the original image (imageFrame) in order to isolate and highlight the detected red regions. By performing a bitwise AND operation between the original image and itself, while using the red_mask as a filter, we can effectively keep only the pixels that correspond to the detected red color, while setting all other pixels to black. This results in an image (res_red) that contains only the areas of the original image where the red color was detected, allowing us to focus on those specific regions for further analysis or visualization.
    #So the bitwise_and function takes the original image twice as arguments along with the mask, and it applies the mask to the image to produce a new image that highlights only the detected color regions. This is a common technique in image processing to isolate specific features based on a binary mask, allowing us to analyze or display only the relevant parts of the image that contain the desired color. By using bitwise AND, we ensure that only the pixels that are both in the original image and in the mask (i.e., the detected color regions) are retained in the resulting image. I however do not see the use of dilation here, I thought it was supposed to enhance the detected regions, but it seems like we are just applying the mask to the original image without any visible effect from the dilation. 
